The paper describes an approach to evolve composite covariance functions for Gaussian processes using genetic programming. This falls under the category of machine learning (cs.LG) as it deals with improving the performance of a model. The use of genetic programming also suggests that the paper may fall under the category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also deals with optimization and search techniques, which could place it under the category of neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) or systems and control (cs.SY). Finally, the paper uses synthetic data and a real-world time series dataset, which suggests that it may fall under the category of data mining (cs.DM).
